    {
      "content": "What is the difference between a public VIP and an internal IP address?",
      "pos": [
        8529,
        8600
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "An internal IP address is an IP address that is assigned to each VM within a VNet by DHCP.",
      "pos": [
        8604,
        8694
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It's not public facing.",
      "pos": [
        8695,
        8718
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you have created a VNet, the internal IP address is assigned from the range that you specified in the subnet settings of your VNet.",
      "pos": [
        8719,
        8853
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you do not have a VNet, an internal IP address will still be assigned.",
      "pos": [
        8854,
        8927
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The internal IP address will remain with the VM for its lifetime, unless that VM is deallocated.",
      "pos": [
        8928,
        9024
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A public VIP is the public IP address that is assigned to your cloud service or load balancer.",
      "pos": [
        9028,
        9122
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It is not assigned directly to your VM NIC.",
      "pos": [
        9123,
        9166
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The VIP stays with the cloud service it is assigned to until all the VMs in that cloud service are deallocated or deleted.",
      "pos": [
        9167,
        9289
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "At that point, it is released.",
      "pos": [
        9290,
        9320
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "What IP address will my VM receive?",
      "pos": [
        9326,
        9361
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Internal IP address -<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> If you deploy a VM to a VNet, the VM receives an internal IP address from a pool of internal IP addresses that you specify.",
      "pos": [
        9365,
        9514
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "VMs communicate within the VNets by using internal IP addresses.",
      "pos": [
        9515,
        9579
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Although Azure assigns a dynamic internal IP address, you can request a static address for your VM.",
      "pos": [
        9580,
        9679
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To learn more about static internal IP addresses, visit <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>How to Set a Static Internal IP<ept id=\"p1\">](virtual-networks-reserved-private-ip.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        9680,
        9811
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>VIP -<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> Your VM is also associated with a VIP, although a VIP is never assigned to the VM directly.",
      "pos": [
        9815,
        9916
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A VIP is a public IP address that can be assigned to your cloud service.",
      "pos": [
        9917,
        9989
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can, optionally, reserve a VIP for your cloud service.",
      "pos": [
        9990,
        10048
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "See <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Reserved Public IP<ept id=\"p1\">](virtual-networks-reserved-public-ip.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        10049,
        10114
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>ILPIP -<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> You can also configure an instance-level public IP address (ILPIP).",
      "pos": [
        10118,
        10197
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "ILPIPs are directly associated with the VM, rather than the cloud service.",
      "pos": [
        10198,
        10272
      ]
